# .trivyignore — waivers for Trivy findings you have reviewed and accepted.
#
# Add one CVE ID per line. Comments above the ID are part of the file's git
# history and become your audit trail for why a finding is not being fixed.
#
# Example:
#
#   # CVE-2025-12345 — libcurl in upstream base. Not reachable from our
#   # deployment (container runs behind mTLS ingress, no outbound HTTP).
#   # Revisit 2026-08 when upstream bumps the base image.
#   CVE-2025-12345
#
# Leave this file empty (except for comments) until you actually need a waiver.
# A waiver without a reason is just a mute button, not evidence.

# CVE-2026-34986 — go-jose JWE decryption panic (HIGH, DoS only).
# Fix lands in go-jose v4.1.4; Gokapi v2.2.4 ships an older version
# and is expected to bump in v2.2.5.
#
# Exploit prerequisite: the JWE decryption path must be active at
# runtime, which only happens when OIDC authentication is configured
# in Gokapi. THEKROLL runs Gokapi internal-only with no OIDC/SSO
# integration, so the vulnerable code path is unreachable.
#
# Impact class: denial of service via panic — not data exposure,
# not code execution. Worst case is an attacker who can already
# trigger an OIDC flow (which they can't here) crashes the service.
#
# Revisit when Gokapi v2.2.5 ships the go-jose bump,
# or by 2026-07 — whichever comes first.
CVE-2026-34986